Question 4

Unimportance: If the arrows coming in or out of a variable are likely to be tiny effects, you can probably delete it.

Redundancy: If variables have arrows coming and going from the same place, we can probably combine them into one.

Mediators: If a variable is only on a graph as a pathway between two other variables, we can probably take it off.

Irrelevance: If a variable is important to the DGP but irrelevant to the specific research question we’re asking, we can probably ignore it in the diagram.

Question 6

Cause: Parenting style

Outcome: Child’s income

Other relevant variables: Parent’s education, parent’s income, child’s education, neighborhood characteristics, race-ethnicity

q6dag <- dagify(
  b ~ a + c + d + e + f + g,
  a ~ c + e + f + g,
  e ~ c + g,
  labels = c(a = "parentingstyle",
             b = "childincome",
             c = "parenteduc",
             d = "childeduc",
             e = "parentinc",
             f = "communitycharacteristics",
             g = "raceethnicity"),
  exposure = "a",
  outcome = "b"
)

set.seed(11111)
ggdag_status(q6dag, use_labels = "label") + theme_dag()
